# Documentation standard — data accuracy (curation over noise)

**Goal:** higher signal for Data and humans by maintaining **truth-aligned knowledge surfaces**, not by adding comments across the codebase “for Data.”

## Preferred surfaces (update these first)

- **System dictionary** — e.g. `renaissance_v4/game_theory/ask_data_system_dictionary_v1.py` and any field/schema dictionaries Data or Ask DATA reads.
- **Static knowledge bundles** — agent / operator context bundles (e.g. `scripts/agent_context_bundle.py` and related pack boundaries).
- **Operator-facing architecture** — sections operators and tools actually use (e.g. game_theory `docs/*ARCHITECTURE*`, student panel dictionary routes).
- **Public API docs** — route and payload contracts that match runtime (`web_app` route docstrings, OpenAPI or inline JSON shapes where maintained).
- **Risky workflow notes** — destructive, ordering, or seam-sensitive flows (short, accurate, near the workflow entry or in the doc above).
- **Shared invariants** — single place for “must never” / “always list” rules Data must not contradict.
- **Field dictionaries** — name → meaning, units, null vs `data_gap`, producer.
- **Bundle boundaries** — what is in / out of this build; honest “not in this build” when something is unavailable.

## Avoid

- Line-by-line or per-function comments whose only purpose is “explaining the code to Data.”
- Low-signal boilerplate (“returns a dict”) and **obvious** code narration.
- Duplicating implementation detail in prose that will **drift** from behavior.
- New markdown files for every conversation unless the user asked for a doc.

## When feedback shows confusion — fix the highest-signal source

| Symptom | Prefer |
|--------|--------|
| Misunderstood **field** | Dictionary / field contract |
| Misunderstood **workflow** | Operator architecture section or risky-workflow note |
| Cannot tell **present vs missing** | `data_gap` / bundle boundary explanation |
| **Invents** unavailable behavior | Document honest boundary: “not in this build” |

## Code comments (narrow exception)

Comments are appropriate when the code is **public API**, **risky**, **operator-facing**, or **enforces an invariant** that humans and tools must share—and a one-line pointer to the canonical doc is better than duplicating paragraphs.

## One-line default

**Curate the knowledge Data reads (dictionary, bundle, contracts, architecture)—do not flood the repo with low-value comments.**
